${V_{{{\mathrm{H}}_{\mathrm{2}}}{\mathrm{O}}}}$\end{document} values gradually decrease, indicating a higher tendency for coordinated H2O molecules to escape, which could weaken the crystal structure. Therefore, while Cu introduction is beneficial, excessive amounts may compromise structural stability. This suggests that the unequal solid-solution phase (Cu1/3Zn2/3)3(OH)2V2O7·2H2O is an optimal choice, balancing high redox activity and structural robustness. This phenomenon, referred to as the solid-solution reinforcement effect, establishes an equilibrium between highly reversible Ca2+ diffusion and effective H2O retention, aligning with the diffusion energy barrier analysis.

